{{Notability||date=June 2017}}{{Refimprove | date = June 2017 }}
'''Respirocytes''' are hypothetical, microscopic, [[Artificial cell|artificial]] [[red blood cell]]s that are intended to emulate the function of their organic counterparts, so as to supplement or replace the function of much of the human body's normal [[respiratory system]]. Respirocytes were proposed by [[Robert A. Freitas Jr]] in his 1998 paper "A Mechanical Artificial Red Blood Cell: Exploratory Design in Medical Nanotechnology".<ref name=ref2>{{cite journal|author=Robert A. Freitas Jr.|title=Exploratory Design in Medical Nanotechnology: A Mechanical Artificial Red Cell|journal=Artificial Cells, Blood Substitutes, and Immobil. Biotech.|number=26|year=1998|pages=411–430}}</ref>
Respirocytes are an example of [[molecular nanotechnology]], a field of technology still in the very earliest, purely hypothetical phase of development. Current technology is not sufficient to build a respirocyte due to considerations of power, atomic-scale manipulation, immune reaction or [[toxicity]], [[computation]] and [[communication]].
== Structure of a respirocyte ==
Freitas proposed a spherical robot made up of 18 billion atoms arranged as a tiny [[pressure tank]], which would be filled up with [[oxygen]] and [[carbon dioxide]].<ref name =REF1>{{cite web|title=RESPIROCYTES – IMPROVING UPON NATURE'S DESIGN: BREATHE EASY WITH RESPIROCYTES|url=http://www.thenanoage.com/respirocytes.htm}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=June 2017}}
[[File:Respirocyte.jpg|thumb|Hypothesised structure of a respirocyte]]
==Uses== In Freitas' proposal, each respirocyte could store and transport 236 times more oxygen than a natural red blood cell, and could release it in a more controlled manner.
[[Ray Kurzweil]] hypothesised that such respirocytes would allow an adult human to [[Sprint (running)|sprint]] at top speed for at least 15 minutes without taking a breath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/TECH/07/15/bio.tech/index.html|title=Scientists: Humans and machines will merge in future|last=Farrar|first=Lara|date=15 July 2008|website=CNN|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-15}}</ref>{{SCIRS|date=June 2017}}{{Medical citation needed|date=June 2017}}
Freitas has also proposed "[[microbivore]]" robots that would attack [[pathogens]] in the manner of [[white blood cells]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Kurzweil | first = Ray | authorlink = Ray Kurzweil | coauthors = | title = The Singularity Is Near | publisher = | date = | location = | pages = 254 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref>
